        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Ad copy</strong> is the written text of any advertisement — the <strong>headline, description lines, display URL, and call-to-action</strong> — designed to persuade a specific audience to click, buy, or convert. On search ads it lives inside strict character limits; on social it competes with a feed for attention. In both cases, copy is what turns impressions into clicks.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Avg. Google Ads CTR</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3.17%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Paid Advertising</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Top-10% CTR</div>
            <div class="tms-value">6%+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">You could have perfect targeting, an unlimited budget, and a great product — but if the copy is weak, people scroll past. Copy is the bridge between seeing the ad and clicking it, and the biggest lever in paid media that does not cost more media spend.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is ad copy?</h2>
        <p>Ad copy is the text component of any advertisement — the words that persuade someone to take action, whether that action is clicking a Google Ad, engaging with a Facebook post, or responding to a billboard. In digital advertising, ad copy includes headlines, description lines, display URLs, and call-to-action text.</p>
        <p>Character limits force discipline. <strong>Google Ads gives you 30 characters per headline and 90 per description.</strong> Meta Ads recommends keeping primary text under 125 characters. LinkedIn Sponsored Content headlines cap at 200. Every character has to earn its place.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why copy is the biggest lever in paid media</div>
          <p>According to WordStream, the average Google Ads CTR across industries is <strong>3.17%</strong>, but the top 10% of ads achieve <strong>6%+ CTR</strong>. The difference is almost always the copy — targeting and bids are widely available; disciplined creative writing is not.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why ad copy matters</h2>
        <p>Bad ad copy wastes budget. Good ad copy makes the same budget work 2–3x harder. Four concrete reasons every paid team obsesses over it:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>CTR determines cost.</strong> In Google Ads, higher CTR improves Quality Score, which lowers your cost per click. Doubling CTR often cuts CPC by 30–50%.</li>
          <li><strong>First impression.</strong> Ad copy is often a prospect's first interaction with your brand. Bland copy, bland impression, no click.</li>
          <li><strong>Conversion alignment.</strong> Great ad copy pre-qualifies clicks by clearly stating the offer, which reduces wasted ad spend on uninterested visitors.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive differentiation.</strong> On a search results page with 4 ads above the fold, copy is the only thing that makes yours stand out at a glance.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How ad copy works</h2>
        <p>Effective ad copy follows patterns, not formulas. The best-performing ads know the pattern and break it intentionally at exactly one point to stand out.</p>

        <h3>The headline does the heavy lifting</h3>
        <p>In Google Ads, roughly 80% of readers see only the headline. It must include the target keyword, communicate the core benefit, and create enough interest to keep reading. Specificity wins:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>"30 SEO Articles/Month — $99" outperforms "Affordable SEO Content Services"</li>
          <li>"Austin Plumber. Here in 60 Min." outperforms "Reliable Plumbing Service"</li>
          <li>"Book a 15-min Demo" outperforms "Get in Touch"</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Description expands and convinces</h3>
        <p>The description line adds proof, handles objections, or clarifies the offer. Numbers work well here: "Join 3,500+ businesses. Cancel anytime. Start for $1." Social proof and risk reversal are your strongest plays.</p>

        <h3>The CTA closes</h3>
        <p>Tell people exactly what to do next. "Get a free audit" beats "Learn more." Specificity in CTAs consistently improves conversion rates. Never make the reader guess what happens after they click.</p>

        <h3>Platform-specific rules</h3>
        <p>Google Ads rewards keyword relevance. Meta Ads rewards emotional engagement and visual-text harmony. LinkedIn Ads respond to professional credibility signals. Write for the platform, not just the product.</p>

        <h2 id="examples">Real ad copy examples that convert</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Business</th><th>Platform</th><th>Copy pattern</th><th>Result</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Emergency plumber</strong></td>
                <td>Google Search</td>
                <td>H1: "Austin Emergency Plumber. Here in 60 Min." · Desc: "Licensed, insured, 4.9★. No overtime charges."</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">CTR 8.4%, CPL cut 42%</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Content SaaS</strong></td>
                <td>Meta</td>
                <td>"Most companies publish 2 blogs/month. The ones ranking on Google publish 30. theStacc automates it — $99/mo."</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">3.1x ROAS vs feature ad</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>B2B analytics tool</strong></td>
                <td>LinkedIn</td>
                <td>"Series-B CROs use [Tool] to spot pipeline gaps 2 weeks earlier."</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">CTR 1.8% (LinkedIn benchmark: 0.4%)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>D2C skincare</strong></td>
                <td>Meta</td>
                <td>Observation → insight → offer: "Most SPF stings your eyes. Ours doesn't. Try our SPF 50 for $12."</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">+38% purchase rate vs feature list</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Ad copy vs landing page copy — how they differ</h2>
        <p>Both persuade, but they operate at different attention spans and commitment levels.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Ad copy</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>3–90 characters per element</li>
              <li>Job: earn the click</li>
              <li>Reader attention: 1–3 seconds</li>
              <li>Optimized for CTR and Quality Score</li>
              <li>Refreshed every 2–4 weeks</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card" style="background: #ecfeff; border-color: #a5f3fc;">
            <h4 style="color: #0e7490;">Landing page copy</h4>
            <ul style="color: var(--text-1);">
              <li>Hundreds to thousands of words</li>
              <li>Job: convert the visitor</li>
              <li>Reader attention: 30 seconds to 5 minutes</li>
              <li>Optimized for conversion rate</li>
              <li>Refreshed quarterly at most</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 ad copy best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lead with the biggest specific number.</strong> "$99/month" beats "affordable." "In 60 minutes" beats "fast."</li>
          <li><strong>Match copy to search intent.</strong> A "compare tools" query needs different copy from a "buy now" query.</li>
          <li><strong>Use the customer's own language.</strong> Mine reviews, sales calls, and Reddit threads for the exact phrases your best customers use.</li>
          <li><strong>Test three copy variants at a time.</strong> One control, two variants. Anything more dilutes traffic per test.</li>
          <li><strong>Include social proof in the description.</strong> "Join 3,500+ businesses" outperforms adjective-heavy copy by 15–25% almost every time.</li>
          <li><strong>End with a specific CTA.</strong> Never "Learn more." Always "Book a demo", "Start a $1 trial", "Get the audit."</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh before ad fatigue hits.</strong> Watch frequency and CTR trend — a rolling 2–4 week refresh keeps performance flat.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — writing the feature list</div>
          <p>The default writer's instinct is to list features. Features do not sell — outcomes do. "AI-powered content generation" is a feature. "30 SEO articles per month, published to your site automatically" is the outcome. Ship the outcome.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common ad copy mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Vague headlines</strong> — "The best solution for your business" says nothing.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring character limits</strong> — Google truncates at exactly 30 characters, mid-word.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing keywords</strong> — search ads without the query keyword lose Quality Score.</li>
          <li><strong>"Click here" CTAs</strong> — never explain what happens after the click.</li>
          <li><strong>Running the same copy for months</strong> — ad fatigue tanks CTR quietly.</li>
          <li><strong>No offer in the ad</strong> — copy that sells the brand instead of the next action.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How long should ad copy be?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>As short as possible while communicating the offer clearly. Google Ads limits headlines to 30 characters and descriptions to 90. Meta Ads best practices suggest under 125 characters for primary text. Use every character to earn the click, not to fill space.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Should I use keywords in ad copy?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>For search ads, absolutely — Google bolds keywords that match the query, which lifts CTR and Quality Score. For social ads, relevance matters more than exact keyword matching. Write for the audience first, then work the keyword in naturally.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How often should I refresh ad copy?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Test new variations every 2–4 weeks. Ad fatigue sets in when the same audience sees the same copy repeatedly, and frequency data will tell you when performance starts declining. Rotate two or three fresh variants at a time so you always have a warm winner.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What makes ad copy convert?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Specificity, a clear offer, social proof, risk reversal, and a CTA that states exactly what happens next. Great ad copy pre-qualifies the click by making the offer unambiguous, which improves both CTR and post-click conversion rate.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Should I write different ad copy per platform?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Google Ads rewards keyword relevance, Meta rewards emotional hooks, and LinkedIn rewards professional credibility. Reusing search-ad headlines on Meta is one of the fastest ways to burn media spend.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

